        <h3>Early history</h3>
        Gambela was established due to its location on the Baro, a tributary of the Nile. Ethiopia and the British considered this to be a great route for shipping products, including coffee, from the lush Ethiopian Highlands to Sudan and Egypt. On May 15, 1902, Emperor Menelik II gave Britain permission to utilise a port along the Baro. A customs post and port were established at Gambela in 1907.Â A 1,366-kilometer shipping line operated by Sudan Railways connected Khartoum with Gambela. By the mid-1930s, boats were sailing twice a month during the rainy season, taking eleven days upstream and seven days downstream, according to Richard Pankhurst.</p>
